com.rockhoppertech.music.midi.js

Class MIDITrack

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.rockhoppertech.music.midi.js.MIDITrack
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Iterable<MIDINote>

    public class MIDITrack
extends Object
implements Serializable, Iterable<MIDINote>
    A collection of MIDINotes and MIDIEvents along with a pile of things you can do to them

    A rewrite of my ancient MIDITrack and MIDINoteList from the 1990s.

    I removed the JavaBean event code, thinking that JavaFX could handle events easily. I've put it back in since I don't want JavaFX classes e.g. javafx.beans.property.DoubleProperty here. So, the onus is on JavaFX authors to handle property change events. Take a look at javafx.beans.property.adapter.JavaBeanStringPropertyBuilder for example.

    Author:
    Gene De Lisa

      • MIDITrack

        public MIDITrack(MIDITrack orig)
        Initializes a new MIDITrack instance as a deep copy of specified MIDITrack. Sort of like a C++ copy constructor (- but without C++ crap like virtual destructors and overloaded operators...) 
         MIDITrack track = new MIDITrack();
 MIDINote note = new MIDINote(Pitch.C5);
 track.add(note);
 MIDITrack trackCopy = new MIDITrack(track);
        Parameters:
        orig - The MIDITrack that will be "cloned".

        public MIDITrack add(MIDINote note)
        Create and append the specified MIDINote to the list. The Note's timing is unchanged. Use append if you want the timing changed.

        PropertyChange MIDITrack.ADD is fired.

 MIDINote note = new MIDINote(Pitch.C5);
 track.add(note);
        Parameters:

        Returns:
        this to cascade

      • map

        public MIDITrack map(NoteModifier mod)
        map is the GoF visitor(331) design pattern. It loops through all the MIDINotes and applies the modifier to each note. Sort of like mapcar in LISP (but Java does not have lambdas - yet - so you need the NoteModifier interface). 
         MIDITrack track = new MIDITrack();
 MIDINote note = new MIDINote(Pitch.C5);
 track.add(note);
 track.map(new DurationModifier(1d, Modifier.Operation.ADD));
        Parameters:
        mod - a NoteModifier implementation.
        Returns:
        this to cascade calls
        See Also:
        Modifier, NoteModifier, ChannelModifier, DurationModifier, InstrumentModifier, PitchModifier, StartBeatModifier

      • map

        public MIDITrack map(MIDINoteModifier mod)
        map is the GoF visitor(331) design pattern. It loops through all the MIDINotes and applies the modifier to each note. Sort of like mapcar in LISP (but Java does not have lambdas - yet - so you need the MIDINoteModifier interface). 
         MIDITrack track = new MIDITrack();
 MIDINote note = new MIDINote(Pitch.C5);
 track.add(note);
 track.map(new VelocityModifier(1d, Modifier.Operation.ADD));
        Parameters:
        mod - a MIDINoteModifier implementation.
        Returns:
        this to cascade calls
        See Also:
        Modifier, MIDINoteModifier, ChannelModifier, InstrumentModifier

      • retrograde

        public final MIDITrack retrograde()
        retrograde reverses the order of the MIDINotes. The start beats are not in order! It's up to you to change those if you so desire. You might use sequential() followed by setStartBeat(). The original track is not modified either.
        Returns:
        a new MIDITrack

      • setStartBeat

        public void setStartBeat(double b)
        setStartBeat sets the start beat of the entire track. This is useful in a GUI where you are moving track representations around. The track needs to be sequential. If the start beats are not in ascending order, it won't work. e.g. When you call retrograde(), the start beats are not in ascending order.
        Parameters:
        b - a double value
